english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Jeon, Lord of Taesan
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Scholars before they rise love to criticize the comings and goings of great ministers at court. Yet when they themselves occupy such a place, they find themselves unable to live by their own words. How much more so when office grows lofty but ambition grows small—when wealth and honor arrive, yet one knows contentment. This is what the worthy men of old and present have found difficult, far beyond the reach of those who merely chatter criticism. Who possesses such virtue? I have seen it in Lord Jeon, the Minister. His name was Wongyun, his courtesy name Jinjeong, a man of Taesan County in Jeonju. His ancestors served as county magistrates, and his father, entering court service, rose to become an official of rank. Through the lord's honor, his father received posthumous promotion. His mother, of the Heo clan, likewise of Taesan's line, was elevated through her son's distinction.

    The Lord was born with unusual brilliance. From youth he bore the gravity of age. At seventeen he passed the examinations at the National Academy. Though he entered office through family privilege—a matter he always regretted—he studied the ancients widely and composed with such skill that even learned scholars felt themselves surpassed. When Emperor Myeongjong ascended the throne, the Lord was summoned to serve in the inner palace. All his duties pleased the sovereign, who recognized his talent and showered him with rewards. Rising through ranks both great and small, he became known throughout the realm.

    When appointed magistrate of Sapsang Province, his integrity was unshakable. He received not a single bribe. Toward the common people, he showed constant compassion born of genuine feeling. Yet toward corrupt officials, he wielded an iron hand—exposing hidden crimes as though blessed with divine sight. All the province stood in respect and fear. In settling legal cases, he was meticulous; even those who received punishment said, "When Lord Jeon judges, what complaint could I have?"

    He rose through ranks of the Censorate, finally becoming Left Vice Minister of the Ministry of Personnel. When a man of power and influence demanded he place his son in office through improper means, the Lord firmly refused. That man harbored deep resentment. Meeting him later on the road, the man attacked him in fury, even kicking him into a ditch. Though the authorities pretended not to notice, all who heard of it did not see it as shameful to the Lord, but rather marveled at his steadfast righteousness.

    Promoted to Governor of Seo-gyeong, he restored order to that tumultuous region through balanced strength and compassion. Not a single person dared deceive the capital. Since recent times, no governor surpassed him. When appointed to inspect three provinces, he praised the virtuous and exposed corruption to universal approval. Every opportunity to promote benefit and eliminate harm, he seized without hesitation. When rebels rose in the east—Uibi and Boryou leading bands of brigands—the Lord was appointed Deputy Commander of the Central Army. The strategies that subdued the rebels and captured the bandit chiefs flowed largely from his counsel. His wisdom was subtle: stationed at Unmun Mountain, while others questioned why he planted gourds beside the granary, he silently revealed to his officers, "The brigands fear we will occupy the heights. They wish us to move. By appearing settled, we slay their hopes." Thus he thought; thus he acted. When the rebels were destroyed, Unmun Mountain stood firm.

    Returned to the capital victorious, he rose through position after position—Vice Minister of Personnel, then Inspector-General, then Right Counselor to the Crown Prince. Finally, in his greatest honor, he was appointed Minister of Works, Chief Minister of the Left—a rank of the first order. The Lord, at this pinnacle, sighed and said: "I rose from nothing. I possessed no great talent, no martial glory to benefit the realm. Yet through the humble work of administration, I have reached the first rank. Is this not enough? Why should I linger?" He requested retirement on grounds of age and illness, so earnestly that the sovereign reluctantly granted it.

    Once released from office, the Lord found peace. He dwelt in a villa west of the capital, wearing simple robes, wandering as he pleased. He gathered with friends over wine, savoring the joy of giving freely. In his seventy-fifth year, he passed away.

    The Lord was circumspect by nature. His policies, once revealed, could not be disputed, for they bore the mark of careful thought. He was sincere and loyal, conducting himself with humility, speaking openly with all, so that people delighted in his company and never tired of it. Yet beneath this gentleness lay an unshakeable core—in matters of principle, he could not be moved.

    He married a woman of the Gye clan and had four sons and four daughters. The eldest son became a palace official; the second took monastic vows and rose to high rank in the sangha; the third became a military officer; the fourth served in the imperial music ministry. All his children made suitable marriages into noble families.

    His sons, having chosen his burial ground, requested me to compose this epitaph. I served with the Lord in the eastern campaign and knew him well. How could I refuse?

    With tears dampening my brush, I inscribe:

    The world grows callous, people grow base,
    Heaven stints in granting worthy souls their place.
    Yet one was born—to whom the Throne gave all,
    Rank, stipend, honor—heeding Virtue's call.

    He took what Heaven sent as precious charge,
    As one who bears a vessel brimmed and large.
    With care that ripples dare not break the surface still,
    He served the State in faithful, tireless will.

    The nation thrived; his own frame grew lean and worn.
    From southern post to western rank adorned,
    The people felt his grace; through court he walked,
    A model for the realm in all he talked.

    First rank achieved, yet like a thorn within—
    Until at last he cast the robes of office skin.
    Then westward to his villa, staff in hand,
    One robe, one staff, in his beloved land.

    What artist could capture what he was in truth?
    His body gone, his name blooms evergreen in proof.
    Upon the histories his radiance shines—
    Th Lord endures though stone holds fast these lines.

    Not dead, I say, but living still through name,
    His line shall flourish, multiply in fame.
    Upon this stone, his epitaph is set,
    To last as long as mountains stand—you may bet.
